Auburn University Land Ownership¶

This year I am working on an undergraduate thesis through the CSRE Department. My thesis is titled "Trajectories of Racialized Power in Auburn, AL" and is an investigation into how the planter class of white elites and Auburn University (AU) have maintianed power over time in the town and surrounding region. I am particularly interested in the spatial organization of power, for example patterns of land ownership and consolidation over time.

For this project I will be examining two datasets: a csv of every present day land parcel and its associated information such as owner, acreage, etc. and a csv with informaion about AU's land acquisition over time. A supplementary dataset is a spreadsheet of AU's enrollment over time.

My central question is:

  • How has land been concentrated in the hands of AU over time?

To gain a more holistic picture of this broad idea of spatial organization of power, some subquestions I will also investigate include:

  • Has land acquisition by AU followed trends of student enrollment?
  • What percentage/how much land does AU own outside of Lee County?

Prepping the Data¶

Because I decided to use data I found myself or was given by AU staff, I did a lot of prep work using scripts on my computer. Below is a summary of the data cleaning I did (mostly using python scripts) prior to uploading it here. >

  • Lee County parcel data
    • Removed columns that contained only NaN values.
    • Removed rows with more than 8 NaN values
    • Filled all NaN cells with ''
    • Created a concated address column with the hopes of geocoding but the address were the owner's address so did not pursure that
  • AU land acquisition data
    • Removed land parcels that had eventually been recended. This was only around 5 of the total acquisitions.
    • Attempted to properly format the dates - this didn't totally work as the original csv was poorly formatted and also excel doesn't handle dates before 1900.
    • Manually added in excel a column that marks if the acquisition of land was in Lee County or outside of it
    • Created a cummulative sum column
    • Manually removed 3 rows with 0 acre values
  • AU enrollment data
    • Seperated school year column into two different columns in excel

AU's Land Ownership in the Present¶

The Lee County parcel spreadsheet is probably the most accurate snapshot of contemporary land ownership, but AU properties are held across several different owner names, as demonstrated below:

In [5]:
owner_sum = lee_parcels.groupby("OWNER").ACRES.sum().reset_index().sort_values("ACRES", ascending=False)
owner_sum[owner_sum.OWNER.str.contains('AUBURN UNIVERSITY')].head(10)

The different owner names immediately reveal that even the idea of "Auburn University" is much more nuanced than one might think. For the purposes of this project I will use the catch all phrase of "Auburn University" and will group all of the above owners together because I think it is perhaps unnecessary (and my time is too limited) to investigate the different types of ownership that Auburn University has. However, the limits of this approach are seen in the stats I have come up with below vs. AU's official stats. According to their website, AU's campus is only 1,841 acres. Since I am intersted in the university's power and importance in town, I think this large discrepancy is insighful in that it reveals AU's land holdings go far beyond what is used for "campus" or traditionally academic pursuits. It could also reveal that my analysis has major flaws.

Summing the above table and then adding it back to the owners sum list as one group gives us a rank of Auburn University as the 2nd largest landowner.

In [6]:

Now, we can see that AU owns 3% of the land in Lee County, which may seem small but is significant. As a comparision to this figure of ~5,900 acres, Stanford owns only 4,017 acres in Santa Clara County (source here). In comparison, this is only .5% of the land. I believe an intersting insight that this data provides is that is illustrates the gaps in research or conversaitons about Auburn University. If you google Stanford and land ownership countless articles show up that discuss the dominance that Stanford has in the Bay Area in terms of land consolidation. No such articles appear when one googles Auburn University, and thus this data supplements my thesis argument that Auburn Univresity is an understudied powerful actor in the Southeast Alabama area. When visualizing a comparision of AU land to even the top 29 other (known) landowners AU pulls far ahead, although of course this visualization is untrustworthy as described above.

AU's Land Ownership Over Time¶

The AU land acquisition data can give insight into several topics. First, we can compare if the acres owned match up to the acres I found from the lee county parcel data.

In [11]:
acres = au_parcels.loc[au_parcels['LEE_COUNTY'] == 1, 'ACREAGE'].sum()
acres_academic = au_parcels[(au_parcels['LEE_COUNTY'] == 1) & (au_parcels['CURRENT_USE'] == 'Academic')].ACREAGE.sum()
print('Lee County acres: ' + acres.astype(str))
print('Lee County academic acres: ' + acres_academic.astype(str))

Lee County acres: 6357.226
Lee County academic acres: 5606.202

We get the new acres value of 6,357, which is higher than the acreage of 5,606 found above and much higher than AU's official campus size of 1,841. This insight reveals the limitations of the Lee County parcel data, because that means AU owns land that is described or notes in some other way than using the actual term "Auburn University." This data also reveals a very interesting question about how AU calculates campus, given that the academic land owned by AU in Lee County is ~3,765 acres greater than the official campus size.

Now let's visualize this accumulation of land over time. First, I am going to create new dataframes in order to isolate land aquired in Lee County vs. outside of Lee County.

In [12]:
au_parcels_lee = au_parcels[au_parcels.LEE_COUNTY == 1].copy()
au_parcels_lee['CUM_ACRES_LEE'] = au_parcels_lee.loc[:, 'ACREAGE'].cumsum()

au_parcels_not_lee = au_parcels[au_parcels.LEE_COUNTY == 0].copy()
au_parcels_not_lee['CUM_ACRES_NOT_LEE'] = au_parcels_not_lee.loc[:, 'ACREAGE'].cumsum()

As demonstrated by the calculations above, out of all of the land that AU owns in the present day, only 22% of the land is in Lee County. The other 88% is elsewhere. This finding is very unexpected to me, and reveals that AU has influence and a presence in a much, much larger area than I originally anticipated.

These charts reveal that the period of around 1930 through 1960 were very important to the university, as not only were frequent purchases of gifts occuring, but the land acquisitions in terms of acreage were also very large. This graph also reveals that it was in around 1930 when the school first started acquiring land outside of Lee County. After a brief qualitative drive, it appears that this increase coincided with a general increase in university prosperity as it bounced back from the Depression.

Number of AES parcels: 86
Percent of AES parcels out of all !Lee County parcels: 80.37383177570094

The land parcels illuminated in the tables above reveal a lot of information that lines up with qualitative research I have done. A section of my thesis focusses on AU's position as the head of Alabama Farmer's Bureau and Agricultural Extension, which allowed AU to hold control over the agricultural sector and individual farmers throughout the 1900s. AU recieved this position in 1915, which is 13 years before AU acquired its first parcel outside of Lee County. However, every single one of the first 10 parcels and 4 of the largest parcels acquired all have the string "AES" in them. In fact, ~80% or 86 parcels acquired by AU outside of Lee County contain the string "AES." AES stands for Agricultural Experiment Station, which I found out because of this project was established all the way in 1883 to "conduct scientific research that would advance Alabamas agricultural and forestry industries" (source). Given this qualitative information, it can be assumed that most of the land acquired by AU over the years outside of Lee County is a part of this relationship that AU shares with the State of Alabama that involves agriculture and forestry research. I believe more research into this land, who exactly controls it, and what the control of so much land in Alabama means for AU's institutional power in the state would be a very interesting project. The work I have seen done that is even remotely similar to these questions I am asking was done by an AU postdoc who investigated who owns timber and forest land in Alabama (link here).

Relationship between student enrollment and land acquisition¶

In order to visualize the relationship between student enrollment and land acquisition, the data will need to be reformatted a bit. The reformating and merging is done below.

In [23]:
grouped_parcels = au_parcels.groupby("year").ACREAGE.sum().reset_index().sort_values("year")
simple_enrollment = au_enrollment[['YearEnd', 'Enrollment']].copy()
simple_enrollment = simple_enrollment.rename(columns={'YearEnd': 'year'})
simple_enrollment['year'] = simple_enrollment['year'].astype('str') 
simple_enrollment['year'] = simple_enrollment['year'].str.replace('.0', '', regex=False)
merged = pd.merge(grouped_parcels, simple_enrollment)
merged['cum_sum'] = merged.loc[:, 'ACREAGE'].cumsum()

Below is a basic visualization for the cummulative acreage accumulation of land by AU and the numbers of student enrollement. Unfortunatly, a major flaw with this data is that I could only figure out how to merge the dataframes in the years that both frames had data. Because there were many years AU did not acquire land, my new merged dataframe is sadly missing immense amounts of info.

In [24]:
base = alt.Chart(merged.reset_index(), title="Student enrollement and land ownership at AU").encode(x='year:T')

alt.layer(
    base.mark_line(color='blue').encode(y=alt.Y('cum_sum', axis=alt.Axis(title='total acres, student enrollment'))),
    base.mark_line(color='red').encode(y='Enrollment')
)
Out[24]:

This looks quite significant, and the correlation statistic of ~.97 as worked out below also demonsrates a strong correlation. However, of course, correlation is not causation so this analysis does not add a ton to this project, but did allow me to practice merging and multi-layer charts!

In [25]:
var_1 = merged['cum_sum']
var_2 = merged['Enrollment']
correlation = var_1.corr(var_2)
